> 1977 Stock 2L, AFC FI, EGR filter recently added.
> 
> So I took my bus into the test station today to get it smogged, and the
> guy informed me that my EGR system is not working right, and he would not
> test it. (I know that it will pass the sniffer, as I just had the CO
> adjusted.)
> 
> He held his hand on the EGR recirculation pipe in the engine bay, and said
> that it was not hot enough, so the EGR system must not be operating
> properly. I pointed out that if I disconeccted the link to the throttle,
> and pushed the valve all the way to the full throttle position, the engine
> speed would rise indicating that the exhaust gas is no longer being
> recirculated. (However moving the lever on the EGR valve all the way to
> the left does not cause the engine speed to rise as expected, which
> indicates that _something_ is wrong with it.)
> 
> He would not test it, and said I have to have it fixed first. I am
> thinking about taking it somewhere else, as my feeling is that he just
> didn't want to test it today as it was close to closing time. However I
> would like to have it working right if possible.
> 
> I know that the EGR valve is NLA, however I am wondering what I should do.
> Is there any way to service the EGR valve? If it is working right does
> that pipe get really hot like he indicated. Should I try replacing it
> with one from a junk yard?
> 
> Any advice would be much appreciated.
> 
> -Nick
